<node TEXT="checksec" ID="ID_1874762863" CREATED="1674949427106" MODIFIED="1697914166418"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE" CONTENT-TYPE="xml/">
<html>
  <head>
    
  </head>
  <body>
    <p>
      checksec &lt;BINARY&gt;
    </p>
    <p>
      The checksec command shows us, the security aspects of the binary, detailed descriptions can be found here. Short explanation for every line:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <b>RELRO</b>: Relocation Read-Only, meaning that the .got section is readonly (Partial RELRO) or both the .got and the .got.plt are readonly (Full RELRO). Also, for RELRO the GOT will be loaded before the BSS into the memory, so it's eliminating the risk of buffer overflows overwriting the GOT.
      </li>
      <li>
        <b>Stack</b>: Tells is, if the stack canaries are used. A stack canary is a (at program start) randomly chosen value, which is pushed on the stack at the beginning of a function and then checked again, before leaving the function. If we want to overwrite the return address using a Buffer Overflow, we have to know this stack canary, else the binary will crash to not cause any damage.
      </li>
      <li>
        <b>NX</b>: If NX is enabled, the stack is usually not executable, so you can only read and write from that section
      </li>
      <li>
        <b>PIE</b>: Position Independent Executable, if enabled, shared libraries are loaded at a randomly chosen address in memory, which makes it more difficult, to just jump to a certain library call. This feature is also called Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR).
      </li>
      <li>
        <b>RWX</b>: Tells us, if the binary has segments, which are writeable and executable at the same time. This allows us to inject and execute code.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      example:
    </p>
    <p>
      checksec vuln, it gives an idea of the architecture!! (Arch!)
    </p>
    <p>
      [*] '/home/unit01/Downloads/vuln'
    </p>
    <p>
      &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Arch:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;i386-32-little
    </p>
    <p>
      &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;RELRO:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Partial RELRO
    </p>
    <p>
      &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Stack:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;No canary found
    </p>
    <p>
      &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;NX:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;NX disabled
    </p>
    <p>
      &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;PIE:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;No PIE (0x8048000)
    </p>
    <p>
      &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;RWX:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Has RWX segments
    </p>
  </body>
</html></richcontent>
<node TEXT="NX enabled?" ID="ID_592963035" CREATED="1679151241421" MODIFIED="1696008785473" LINK="https://ctf101.org/binary-exploitation/no-execute/"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE" CONTENT-TYPE="xml/">
<html>
  <head>
    
  </head>
  <body>
    <p>
      The No eXecute or the NX bit (also known as Data Execution Prevention or DEP) marks certain areas of the program as not executable, meaning that stored input or data cannot be executed as code. This is significant because it prevents attackers from being able to jump to custom shellcode that they've stored on the stack or in a global variable.
    </p>
    <p>
      In short:
    </p>
    <p>
      If NX is enabled you cannot execute of the stack, so&nbsp;&nbsp;you cannot use shellcode, so you have to do Remote Oriented Programming
    </p>
    <p>
      if it is not enabled, you can load a shellcode in the stack and have fun
    </p>
  </body>
</html></richcontent>
